      <byline class="print_byline">By ELSA BRENNER</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Brenner, Elsa</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Seattle-based Recreational Equipment Inc, which had outlet in New Rochelle, NY, for last 11 years, is seeking another location in New York or Connecticut to generate more retail sales (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The outdoor sports retailer Recreational Equipment Inc., situated for the last 11 years in New Rochelle, is looking for a new home where it will get more traffic.</p>
        <p>The Seattle-based REI is the leading retail and online merchant of outdoor gear and clothing with 57 retail stores in 23 states and Japan; three online stores (www.rei.com. www.rei-outlet.com and www.rei .co.jp in Japan) and an adventure travel company, REI Adventures.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The outdoor sports retailer Recreational Equipment Inc., situated for the last 11 years in New Rochelle, is looking for a new home where it will get more traffic.</p>
        <p>The Seattle-based REI is the leading retail and online merchant of outdoor gear and clothing with 57 retail stores in 23 states and Japan; three online stores (www.rei.com. www.rei-outlet.com and www.rei .co.jp in Japan) and an adventure travel company, REI Adventures.</p>
        <p>Michael Collins, a spokesman for the store, said REI hopes to find another location in New York or Connecticut, which will generate more retail sales.</p>
        <p>The current 45,000-square-foot former W. T. Grant department store, which closed in 1976, is REI's only retail outlet in the New York metropolitan region.</p>
        <p>ELSA BRENNER</p>
        <p>IN BRIEF</p>
      </block>
